<br>
As far as Judiasm and the messianic concept goes, it makes us a much stronger and ambitious group.  We feel it's our duty to do as much good in our lives as possible, and that every little bit helps.  Sometimes just doing that good is enough to give meaning to life, because you're working to make the world a better place for the people you love and for the children that will inevitably inherit the earth.  Knowing you've helped, even in some small way, gives a sense of accomplishment and worth.  Whether or not it looks like a losing battle, it's still one worth fighting.  If the news covered acts of kindness the way they cover acts of cruelty I think many people's viewpoints would change.<br>
<br>
As far as knowing the exact second when my grandma died - we had been with her in the hospital for 2 weeks while she was intubated and dying from a combination of leukemia and pneumonia.  I had been sad and tormented the whole time.  I finally went home one day to cook dinner, and while I was driving it was raining like crazy.  Then poof, all of a sudden I was ridiculously happy - couldn't stop smiling and laughing.  I looked up, saw a huge double arch rainbow and said, &quot;Grandma's dead.&quot;  I pulled into the driveway of my house, saw my Dad looking sad and he said, &quot;Sweetie, your grandmother died while you were driving home, about 3 minutes ago (which was  when I'd had the smiling/laughing/crying fit).  We need to go back to the hospital.&quot;  And I heard her say to me, &quot;You know I'm  happy now and not in pain.  I need you to clean the house and fix dinner because your mother shouldn't have to deal with this.  I need you to take care of her for me.&quot;  <br>
<br>
So I stayed home and I cleaned the house like mad and made a great dinner, and told everyone about the rainbow, and it cheered them up...  To make things even more freaky, my cousin, Jenifer also saw a rainbow at the same time, and called me at home immediately after Dad left and said, &quot;Rae, is Grandma dead? I just got the weirdest sense that she's gone.&quot;  Totally trippy, but enough to convince me.  No one had time to call Jen to tell her to get on a plane.  She just up and called me, just as Dad left the house to go comfort Mom.<br>
<br>
Also, I think I need to clarify my belief as to what God is.  I was checking out the free classes that MIT has online about philosophy and it made me realize there is room in the description of my belief system for confusion.<br>
<br>
I do not believe in an omniscient, omnipotent, thoroughly good God.  I believe in a life force that binds us all together, that exists whether or not we do, and that is indiscriminate in giving and taking life.  I do not believe in heaven.  I do not believe in hell.  I just believe in doing what is right - and I define what is right by doing what will cause the most good for the most people for the longest amount of time.  I believe that bad things happen to good people for no reason at all, and that the only true rewards you will receive are those you earn.<br>
<br>
Also as for who created God - that's a fabulous question.  I believe that the word God and the way that most people think of him/her/it is entirely manmade and does exist to offer comfort and a structure for living.  As for the higher power I speak of, I couldn't begin to say who or what would have created it.  All I know is that there is sufficient evidence to prove to me that it does exist.<br>
<br>
I'm sure the next question would be to present that evidence, which would be more than fair.  All I can say is to look around and see the magnificent balance that our world is constantly in.  Yes, shitty things happen every day, but so do wonderful things.  I see the beauty in music and in mosquitos, even if they piss me off... and I see the splendor of love and the horrid pain of loss.  I see pollution, global warming, terrorism, rape, incest, and murder... and I also see volunteers cleaning beaches, treating strangers for diseases, teaching, building... people in happy families giving birth to wanted babies, and wrongs being punished by people like my father. (He's a prosecutor.)<br>
<br>
I simply believe the spirit of life and creation refuses to be repressed, and that ultimately, whether or not we die in a nuclear holocaust, it will survive without us.  I just choose to recognize its presence.  <p></p><span class=m><i></i></span><hr size=1>   &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fbbardenfrm57.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=41.topic&index=23><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/reply.gif border=0 width=20 height=20 alt="reply to this message" align=absmiddle></a>   <br><br></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td colspan=2><table cellpadding=8 cellspacing=0 width=100%><tr><td nowrap width=20% valign=top><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bbbarden.showUserPublicProfile?gid=confound>CoNfOuNd</A> </span><br><BR><img src=http://peter.armo.co.uk/img/irish.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60><br> <span class=usertitle>Createur de Projets<br /><img src='http://www.bbarden.com/img/levels/userlevel-admin.gif' /><br /><img src='http://www.bbarden.com/img/levels/userlevel-vip.gif' /></span><br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m width=80%><span class=m><font color=#FF0000>Posted: 10/14/02 11:01:40 pm</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span><br><span class=title> Re: -</span><hr size=1> I don't think you believe in the kind of God most Christians do. I can't seperate Jews and Christians, as if there is a difference I fail to know it.<br>
